def reset_Dataset(_batch_size=32, _color_mode="grayscale", scale=None, _shuffle=True): 
  dataGenerator = preprocessing.image.ImageDataGenerator(
      rescale=scale
  )
  print("TrainData: ")
  TrainData = dataGenerator.flow_from_directory(
    "/content/Data/train",
    target_size = (80, 80),
    color_mode = _color_mode,
    batch_size = _batch_size,
    shuffle=_shuffle
  )

  print("TestData: ")
  TestData = dataGenerator.flow_from_directory(
    "/content/Data/test",
    target_size = (80, 80),
    color_mode = _color_mode,
    batch_size = _batch_size,
    shuffle=_shuffle
  )
  return TrainData, TestData

In [22]:
def create_neural_network(_activation, summary=False):
  input = layers.Input(shape=(80, 80, 1))
  output = layers.Flatten()(input)
  output = layers.Dense(1024, activation=_activation)(output)
  output = layers.Dense(1024, activation=_activation)(output)
  output = layers.Dense(3, activation="softmax")(output)
  model = models.Model(inputs=input, outputs=output)
  model.compile(optimizer=optimizers.SGD(learning_rate=0.01), loss="categorical_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"])
  if summary == True:
    model.summary()
  else:
    history = model.fit(TrainData, validation_data=TestData, epochs=10)
    return model, history

From each neuron to all the neurons of the next layer is connected a weighted edge.

In the first hidden layer we have 6400 weight and 1 bias, and since we have 1024 neurons, we have 6400 x 1024 weight and 1024 bias.

In the second hidden layer we have 1024 to weight and 1 bias, and since we have 1024 to neurons, we have 1024 x 1024 to weight and 1024 to bias.

In the last layer we have 1024 weights and 1 bias, and since we have 3 neurons we have 1024 x 3 weights and 3 biases.

As a result, we have a total of 7607,299 parameters for neural network training.

In [15]:
def print_report(history):
  labels = [classes_labels[i] for i in range(len(classes_labels))]
  y_true_train = TrainData_not_shuffle.labels
  y_predict_train = np.argmax(history.predict(TrainData_not_shuffle), axis=1)

  y_true_test = TestData_not_shuffle.labels
  y_predict_test = np.argmax(history.predict(TestData_not_shuffle), axis=1)

  print("TrainData: ")
  print(classification_report(y_true_train, y_predict_train, target_names=labels))
  print("TestData: ")
  print(classification_report(y_true_test, y_predict_test, target_names=labels))
In [16]:
def visualization(history):
  plt.figure(figsize = (5, 5)) 

  plt.plot(history.history['loss'], label='Train')
  plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'], label='Test')

  plt.title("Model Loss")
  plt.xlabel("Epochs")
  plt.ylabel("Loss")

  plt.legend()
  plt.show()

  plt.figure(figsize = (5, 5)) 

  plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'], label='Train')
  plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'], label='Test')

  plt.title("Model Accuracy")
  plt.xlabel("Epochs")
  plt.ylabel("Accuracy")

  plt.legend()
  plt.show()

Question One:¶

The relu output range between zero and infinite positive.

Because we have not normalized the data, we have a gradient explosion and the value of the parameters overflows.

To solve this problem, we need to normalize the data.

Question Two:¶

The tanh output range is from negative one to positive one, and if the input tends to infinity, the output of the function tends to one, so we will not have the overflow problem.

But the slope of the length changes relative to the step width decreases and the derivative of the tanh function tends to zero, which causes network learning to be incomplete and the neural network to not work well on all data.

To solve this problem, it will be useful to normalize the data because the value of the derivative of the hyperbolic tangent function will be zero as much as possible.

Question Three:¶

The reason for the different observations about the two functions is due to the different output intervals of these two functions as well as the input range of these two functions.

The common denominator of both our models and solutions is that the input data of both of them need to be normalized in order for the network to be well trained.

Step 5:¶

In this section, although the structure we have calculates the value of F1 to be about 90%, I used two functions to get the maximum value for F1.

At first, I changed the activation function to a hyperbolic tangent, but I did not get the desired result.

Then I changed the structure of the neural network by changing the number of layers and the number of neurons in each layer and reached f1 about 95%.

In [69]:
def create_neural_network_with_extra_layers(_activation, epochs=10, summary=False, optimizer=optimizers.SGD(learning_rate=0.01)
    , loss="categorical_crossentropy"):
  input = layers.Input(shape=(80, 80, 1))
  output = layers.Flatten()(input)
  output = layers.Dense(2048, activation=_activation)(output)
  output = layers.Dense(4096, activation=_activation)(output)
  output = layers.Dense(1024, activation=_activation)(output)
  output = layers.Dense(3, activation="softmax")(output)
  model = models.Model(inputs=input, outputs=output)
  model.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss=loss, metrics=["accuracy"])
  if summary == True:
    model.summary()
  else:
    history = model.fit(TrainData, validation_data=TestData, epochs=epochs)
    return model, history

Step 6:¶

Question One:¶

In general, we use optimizers to optimize and fix problems during neural network training operations.

Momentum is a parameter like the learning rate parameter.

Because our data contains noise data, we may make an error in updating the weights and get stuck in the local minimums and the network training will stop.

This parameter helps to cross the local minimums to continue the progress of network training.

Question Three:¶

No, too much value for the momentum takes us away from the desired result.

And instead of jumping on local minima, he jumps on ideal weights.

That is, Adam's optimizer is faster but not more efficient.

Question Two:¶

We need enough epochs to train an optimal neural network.

Because network performance improves step by step.

This means that we need to review and analyze the training data several times and update the weights, so that the weights are updated each time and get closer to their optimal value.

Question Three:¶

Using a large number of epochs is not necessarily appropriate.

Because it increases the training time of the model and reduces the training speed of the neural network, and that it increases the possibility of the model becoming orphaned, it means that our model is trained on noise data and the model works very well on training data but does not work well on test data.

To avoid this problem, the training process should be stopped before reducing the accuracy of the model on the test data.

Question One:¶

As you can see, the accuracy and parameters of F1, recall and precision are drastically reduced, and for two of the classes we have the value of F1 equal to zero.

Question Two:¶

Because in mse it is assumed that our data has a normal or Gaussian distribution, it will not be useful in classification problems and will not give us optimal output and its application is in regression problems.

And that models like the mse probability model, which distinguish the correct class with little difference, will not necessarily give us the desired optimal result.

And in these models, the amount of loss may be calculated incorrectly.

Step 9:¶

These two models prevent the neural network from orphiting the data.

In L2 method, sudden weight gain is prevented and its function is to try to keep the weights small.

In the dropout method, a small portion of the input data is excluded from the calculations based on a probabilistic parameter.

As a result, the number of uses and the amount of probabilistic parameters of this function should be normal, and if a lot of data is taken out of the calculations, the accuracy of the model will decrease.

As you will see, in the L2 model we will increase the value of F1 and it will be 95%, but in the dropout model we will decrease the value of F1 because we have taken a lot of data out of the calculation.

In [78]:
def create_neural_network_with_regularizer(_activation, epochs=10, summary=False, optimizer=optimizers.SGD(learning_rate=0.01)
    , loss="categorical_crossentropy"):
  input = layers.Input(shape=(80, 80, 1))
  output = layers.Flatten()(input)
  output = layers.Dense(2048, activation=_activation, kernel_regularizer=regularizers.L2(l2=0.0001))(output)
  output = layers.Dense(4096, activation=_activation, kernel_regularizer=regularizers.L2(l2=0.0001))(output)
  output = layers.Dense(1024, activation=_activation, kernel_regularizer=regularizers.L2(l2=0.0001))(output)
  output = layers.Dense(3, activation="softmax", kernel_regularizer=regularizers.L2(l2=0.0001))(output)
  model = models.Model(inputs=input, outputs=output)
  model.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss=loss, metrics=["accuracy"])
  if summary == True:
    model.summary()
  else:
    history = model.fit(TrainData, validation_data=TestData, epochs=epochs)
    return model, history

def create_neural_network_with_dropout(_activation, epochs=10, summary=False, optimizer=optimizers.SGD(learning_rate=0.01)
    , loss="categorical_crossentropy"):
  input = layers.Input(shape=(80, 80, 1))
  output = layers.Flatten()(input)
  output = layers.Dense(2048, activation=_activation)(output)
  output = layers.Dropout(rate=0.1)(output)
  output = layers.Dense(4096, activation=_activation)(output)
  output = layers.Dropout(rate=0.1)(output)
  output = layers.Dense(1024, activation=_activation)(output)
  output = layers.Dropout(rate=0.1)(output)
  output = layers.Dense(3, activation="softmax")(output)
  model = models.Model(inputs=input, outputs=output)
  model.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss=loss, metrics=["accuracy"])
  if summary == True:
    model.summary()
  else:
    history = model.fit(TrainData, validation_data=TestData, epochs=epochs)
    return model, history
